      <div xml:id="NA88-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu (ET: varaiyātu vantoḻukun talaimakaṉ; EV: talaivaṉ) ciṟaippuṟamākat tōḻi talaivikku uraippāḷāyc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said as one who is talking to HER while [HE] is behind the fence.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA88">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            yāñcey tolviṉaik kevaṉpē tuṟṟaṉai</l>
<l>            varuntal vāḻi nīyeṉa yāñceṉ</l>
<l>            ṟuraittaṉam varuka meḻumati puṇartiraik</l>
<l>            kaṭalviḷai yamutam peyaṟkēṟ ṟāaṅ</l>
<l>            kuruki yalkuta lañcuva lutukkāṇ </l>
<l>            ṭammōṉ koṭumai namvayi ṉeṟṟi</l>
<l>            nayamperi tuṭaimaiyiṟ ṟāṅkal cellātu</l>
<l>            kaṇṇī raruvi yāka</l>
<l>            vaḻumē tōḻiyavar paḻamutir kuṉṟē.</l>
        </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>What confusion did you have about the old work to be done by us?</l>
<l>Rise, let’s go, talk [to him and] come [back],<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ceṉṟu uraittaṉam varukam eḻumati</term>: here we find a row of one absolutive, two <term xml:lang="ta">muṟṟeccam</term>-s and an imperative that express a temporal sequence by marking the aspect, while the actual finite form is <term xml:lang="ta">eḻumati</term> at the end, the actual prelude to the action to be accomplished.</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">saying “don't suffer, may you live”.</l>
<l rend="indent4">I fear</l>
<l rend="indent">[our] staying [there], dissolving like the ambrosia, ripened by the sea</l>
<l rend="indent3">of uniting waves, when exposed(?) to the rain.</l>
<l rend="indent4">See there:</l>
<l>His fruit-ripening hill is crying, friend,</l>
<l rend="indent2">with waterfalls for tears,</l>
<l rend="indent3">unable to bear<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tāṅkal cellātu</term>: how to understand this construction - the waterfall is one that cannot arrive at bearing?</note> because it is full of longing,</l>
<l rend="indent3">while its master strikes at us with [his] cruelty.<note place="foot">Here the identification between HER and the land described goes so far as to attribute the hill with HER feelings for the man.</note></l>
        </lg>
